solution.p:
Here we want to compute the average value of C(x) over the interval [0,200], that is
C_{\operatorname{AVG} [0,200]} =\mathstrut \amp \frac{1}{200-0} \cdot \int\limits_0^{200} (0.4x^2+140x+110) \, dx =\mathstrut \amp \left.\frac{1}{200}\left(0.4\frac{x^3}{3}+140\frac{x^2}{2}+110x\right)\right|_0^{200}
=\mathstrut \amp \frac{1}{200}\left(\frac{0.4}{3}(200)^3+70(200)^2+110(200)\right) =\mathstrut \amp 19443.30

statement.p:
Therefore, the area between the curves y=x^2+1 and y=x+3 is given by the following quantity:
\int\limits_{-1}^{2}(x+3)dx-\int\limits_{-1}^{2}(x^2+1)dx \amp=\int\limits_{-1}^{2}\left((x+3)-(x^2+1)\right)dx
\mathstrut \amp=\int\limits_{-1}^{2}(-x^2+x+2)dx \mathstrut \amp=\left. -\frac{1}{3}x^3+\frac{1}{2}x^2+2x \right|_{-1}^{2} \mathstrut \amp= -\frac{1}{3}(2)^3+\frac{1}{2}(2)^2+2(2)-\left(-\frac{1}{3}(-1)^3+\frac{1}{2}(-1)^2+2(-1)\right) \mathstrut \amp =-\frac{8}{3}+2+4-\left(\frac{1}{3}+\frac{1}{2}-2\right) \mathstrut \amp= \frac{9}{2}
